      </div>

      <div id="placeholder" class="card">
        <div class="ph-eq">P = &rho;&middot;g&middot;H</div>
        <div class="ph-sub">Select fluid &middot; set value &middot; press convert</div>
        <div class="ph-examples">
          <div class="ph-ex">&#x25BA; 10 m of <strong>water</strong> = 0.981 bar = 14.22 psi</div>
          <div class="ph-ex">&#x25BA; 10 m of <strong>mercury</strong> = 13.29 bar = 192.8 psi</div>
          <div class="ph-ex">&#x25BA; 1 bar = 10.20 m of water = 33.47 ft</div>
          <div class="ph-ex">&#x25BA; 1 psi = 0.703 m H&sup2;O = 2.307 ft H&sup2;O</div>
          <div class="ph-ex">&#x25BA; 760 mmHg = 1 atm = 10.33 m H&sup2;O</div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div><!-- /Right -->

  </div><!-- /main-grid -->


  <!-- ENGINEERING REFERENCE -->
  <section id="learn" style="margin-top:52px">
    <div class="section-ttl">Engineering Reference</div>
    <p class="section-sub">Physics, formulas and practical guidance for every engineer</p>

    <div class="edu-grid">

      <div class="edu-card">
        <div class="edu-card-hd"><div class="edu-num">1</div><div class="edu-ttl">The Fundamental Formula</div></div>
        <div class="edu-bd">
          The relationship between <strong>fluid head H</strong> and <strong>pressure P</strong>
          comes from hydrostatics:
          <div class="eqb">
            <span class="kw">P = &rho; &times; g &times; H</span><br>
            <span class="kw">H = P / (&rho; &times; g)</span><br>
            <span class="nt">P = pressure (Pa) &nbsp;|&nbsp; &rho; = density (kg/m&sup3;)</span><br>
            <span class="nt">g = gravity (m/s&sup2;) &nbsp;|&nbsp; H = head (m)</span>
          </div>
          Head is <strong>fluid-specific</strong>. 10 m of mercury exerts 13.5&times; more pressure
          than 10 m of water.
          <div class="infobox">
            &nbsp;&#x2139;&nbsp; Quick check: 1 m of water at 20&deg;C &asymp; 0.0979 bar &asymp; 1.420 psi &asymp; 9.79 kPa.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="edu-card">
        <div class="edu-card-hd"><div class="edu-num">2</div><div class="edu-ttl">Why Pump Curves Use Head</div></div>
        <div class="edu-bd">
          Centrifugal pump curves are in <strong>metres of head</strong> — the same impeller
          at the same speed produces the same head for any fluid.<br><br>
          Example &mdash; 50 m head pump:
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Water</strong> (998 kg/m&sup3;) &rarr; 4.89 bar</li>
            <li><strong>Diesel</strong> (840 kg/m&sup3;) &rarr; 4.12 bar</li>
            <li><strong>Sulfuric acid</strong> (1840 kg/m&sup3;) &rarr; 9.01 bar</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="notebox">
            &nbsp;&#x26A0;&nbsp; Never size pipe or valves using water pressure if pumping a denser fluid like acid, brine, or mercury.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="edu-card">
        <div class="edu-card-hd"><div class="edu-num">3</div><div class="edu-ttl">Temperature &amp; Density</div></div>
        <div class="edu-bd">
          Most liquids expand when heated &mdash; density decreases.
          <div class="eqb">
            <span class="kw">&rho;(T) &asymp; &rho;&sub2;&sub0; &times; [1 &minus; &beta; &times; (T &minus; 20)]</span><br>
            <span class="nt">&beta; = thermal expansion coefficient (1/&deg;C)</span><br>
            <span class="nt">Water: &beta; &asymp; 2.1&times;10&sup2;/&deg;C</span>
          </div>
          <table>
            <thead><tr><th>Temp</th><th>Water &rho; (kg/m&sup3;)</th><th>m per bar</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>4&deg;C</td><td>1000.0</td><td>10.197</td></tr>
              <tr><td>20&deg;C</td><td>998.2</td><td>10.215</td></tr>
              <tr><td>60&deg;C</td><td>983.2</td><td>10.372</td></tr>
              <tr><td>100&deg;C</td><td>958.4</td><td>10.639</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
          For organic solvents &beta; is 4&ndash;7&times; higher &mdash; always apply temperature correction.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="edu-card">
        <div class="edu-card-hd"><div class="edu-num">4</div><div class="edu-ttl">Pressure Unit Conversions</div></div>
        <div class="edu-bd">
          <div class="eqb">
            <span class="kw">1 bar = 100,000 Pa</span><br>
            <span class="kw">1 psi = 6,894.757 Pa</span><br>
            <span class="kw">1 atm = 101,325 Pa</span><br>
            <span class="kw">1 mmHg = 133.322 Pa</span><br>
            <span class="nt">1 bar &asymp; 14.504 psi &asymp; 0.987 atm &asymp; 750.1 mmHg</span>
          </div>
          <table>
            <thead><tr><th>Unit</th><th>Typical Use</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>bar / mbar</td><td>Process plants, Europe</td></tr>
              <tr><td>psi / psig</td><td>USA industry, piping</td></tr>
              <tr><td>kPa / MPa</td><td>SI standard, civil</td></tr>
              <tr><td>atm</td><td>Chemistry, altitude</td></tr>
              <tr><td>mmHg / inHg</td><td>Medical, barometers</td></tr>
              <tr><td>m H&sub2;O / ft H&sub2;O</td><td>Pumps, HVAC</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="edu-card">
        <div class="edu-card-hd"><div class="edu-num">5</div><div class="edu-ttl">Gauge vs Absolute Pressure</div></div>
        <div class="edu-bd">
          <div class="eqb">
            <span class="kw">P_abs = P_gauge + P_atm</span><br>
            <span class="nt">P_atm = 1.01325 bar = 14.696 psia</span>
          </div>
          <strong>Absolute pressure</strong> is measured from perfect vacuum.
          Used for NPSH, vapour pressure, and gas law calculations.<br><br>
          <strong>Gauge pressure</strong> is measured above atmospheric.
          What industrial gauges display.
          <div class="notebox">
            &nbsp;&#x26A0;&nbsp; For NPSHa calculations always use absolute pressures.
            See our <a href="/npsh-calculator/" style="color:var(--navy);font-weight:600">NPSH Calculator</a>.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="edu-card">
        <div class="edu-card-hd"><div class="edu-num">6</div><div class="edu-ttl">Specific Gravity &amp; Custom Fluids</div></div>
        <div class="edu-bd">
          <strong>Specific gravity (SG)</strong> = fluid density / 1000 (dimensionless):
          <div class="eqb">
            <span class="kw">SG = &rho;_fluid / 1000</span><br>
            <span class="kw">P = H &times; SG &times; 1000 &times; g</span><br>
            <span class="nt">For slurries: &rho;_mix = &rho;_liq &times;(1&minus;Cv) + &rho;_sol &times;Cv</span>
          </div>
          Common SG: diesel 0.84 &middot; seawater 1.025 &middot; H&sub2;SO&sub4; 1.84 &middot; mercury 13.55
          <div class="infobox">
            &nbsp;&#x2139;&nbsp; Enter SG in the Custom Density panel for any slurry, blend, or mixture.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="edu-card" style="grid-column: 1 / -1">
        <div class="edu-card-hd"><div class="edu-num">7</div><div class="edu-ttl">How to Read Pump Curves</div></div>
        <div class="edu-bd">

          <p style="margin-bottom:12px">
            A <strong>pump performance curve</strong> is a graph published by the pump manufacturer showing how a specific
            pump model behaves across its full operating range. Understanding it is essential for correct pump selection,
            system design, and troubleshooting. Every pump curve contains the same core elements.
          </p>

          <!-- SVG Pump Curve Diagram -->
          <div style="background:var(--bg); border:1px solid var(--border); border-radius:var(--r2); padding:20px; margin:14px 0; overflow-x:auto">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 620 320" width="100%" style="max-width:620px; display:block; margin:0 auto; font-family:'DM Sans',sans-serif">

              <!-- Grid lines -->
              <defs>
                <pattern id="grid" width="52" height="40" patternUnits="userSpaceOnUse" x="60" y="20">
                  <path d="M 52 0 L 0 0 0 40" fill="none" stroke="#e5e7eb" stroke-width="1"/>
                </pattern>
              </defs>
              <rect x="60" y="20" width="520" height="240" fill="url(#grid)"/>
              <rect x="60" y="20" width="520" height="240" fill="none" stroke="#d1d5db" stroke-width="1.5"/>

              <!-- Axis labels -->
              <text x="320" y="315" text-anchor="middle" fill="#6b7280" font-size="12" font-weight="600">Flow Rate Q (m³/h)</text>
              <text x="14" y="140" text-anchor="middle" fill="#6b7280" font-size="12" font-weight="600" transform="rotate(-90,14,140)">Head H (m)</text>
              <text x="595" y="140" text-anchor="middle" fill="#6b7280" font-size="11" transform="rotate(90,595,140)">Efficiency η (%)  /  Power P (kW)</text>

              <!-- X axis ticks & labels -->
              <text x="60"  y="278" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="10">0</text>
              <text x="164" y="278" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="10">50</text>
              <text x="268" y="278" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="10">100</text>
              <text x="372" y="278" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="10">150</text>
              <text x="476" y="278" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="10">200</text>
              <text x="580" y="278" text-anchor="middle" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="10">250</text>

              <!-- Y axis ticks & labels (Head) -->
              <text x="52" y="264" text-anchor="end" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="10">0</text>
              <text x="52" y="224" text-anchor="end" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="10">10</text>
              <text x="52" y="184" text-anchor="end" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="10">20</text>
              <text x="52" y="144" text-anchor="end" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="10">30</text>
              <text x="52" y="104" text-anchor="end" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="10">40</text>
              <text x="52" y="64"  text-anchor="end" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="10">50</text>
              <text x="52" y="24"  text-anchor="end" fill="#9ca3af" font-size="10">60</text>

              <!-- H-Q CURVE (navy, bold) — falls from top-left to bottom-right -->
              <path d="M 60,52 C 130,56 220,72 320,120 C 400,158 470,200 580,258"
                    fill="none" stroke="#1a3a6b" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round"/>
              <text x="90" y="48" fill="#1a3a6b" font-size="11" font-weight="700">H-Q curve</text>

              <!-- EFFICIENCY CURVE (green, dashed) — bell shape peaking around BEP -->
              <path d="M 100,255 C 160,230 240,130 320,108 C 390,90 440,105 510,155 C 540,178 560,210 580,240"
                    fill="none" stroke="#15803d" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="6,3" stroke-linecap="round"/>
              <text x="310" y="96" fill="#15803d" font-size="11" font-weight="600">η curve</text>

              <!-- POWER CURVE (amber) — rises left to right -->
              <path d="M 60,240 C 150,228 270,210 380,195 C 460,184 520,178 580,172"
                    fill="none" stroke="#e8920a" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
              <text x="430" y="172" fill="#e8920a" font-size="11" font-weight="600">P curve</text>

              <!-- SYSTEM CURVE (dashed red) — parabola from origin -->
              <path d="M 60,260 C 150,245 250,200 360,148 C 430,115 500,90 560,68"
                    fill="none" stroke="#dc2626" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="5,4" stroke-linecap="round"/>
              <text x="530" y="58" fill="#dc2626" font-size="11" font-weight="600">System</text>

              <!-- OPERATING POINT — intersection of H-Q and system curve -->
              <!-- Approx intersection at Q≈150, H≈120 → svg x=372, y=120 -->
              <circle cx="372" cy="120" r="7" fill="white" stroke="#1a3a6b" stroke-width="2.5"/>
              <circle cx="372" cy="120" r="3" fill="#1a3a6b"/>
              <!-- Drop lines -->
              <line x1="372" y1="120" x2="372" y2="260" stroke="#1a3a6b" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4,3" opacity="0.5"/>
              <line x1="60"  y1="120" x2="372" y2="120" stroke="#1a3a6b" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4,3" opacity="0.5"/>
              <text x="376" y="115" fill="#1a3a6b" font-size="10" font-weight="700">Operating</text>
              <text x="376" y="127" fill="#1a3a6b" font-size="10" font-weight="700">Point</text>

              <!-- BEP marker on efficiency curve — peak ~Q=150 -->
              <circle cx="320" cy="108" r="5" fill="#15803d" opacity="0.85"/>
              <text x="286" y="100" fill="#15803d" font-size="10" font-weight="700">BEP</text>

              <!-- NPSH required curve (light blue, at bottom) -->
              <path d="M 60,250 C 160,248 280,244 380,236 C 460,230 520,220 580,206"
                    fill="none" stroke="#0ea5e9" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="3,3"/>
              <text x="450" y="222" fill="#0ea5e9" font-size="10" font-weight="600">NPSHr</text>

              <!-- Shutoff head label -->
              <text x="64" y="49" fill="#374151" font-size="10">Shutoff</text>
              <text x="64" y="60" fill="#374151" font-size="10">head</text>

            </svg>
          </div>

          <!-- Legend -->
          <div style="display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; gap:10px; margin-bottom:14px">
            <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:6px;font-family:var(--mono);font-size:.68rem;color:var(--txt2)">
              <svg width="28" height="4"><line x1="0" y1="2" x2="28" y2="2" stroke="#1a3a6b" stroke-width="3"/></svg> H-Q Curve
            </div>
            <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:6px;font-family:var(--mono);font-size:.68rem;color:var(--txt2)">
              <svg width="28" height="4"><line x1="0" y1="2" x2="28" y2="2" stroke="#15803d" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="6,3"/></svg> Efficiency &eta;
            </div>
            <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:6px;font-family:var(--mono);font-size:.68rem;color:var(--txt2)">
              <svg width="28" height="4"><line x1="0" y1="2" x2="28" y2="2" stroke="#e8920a" stroke-width="2"/></svg> Power P
            </div>
            <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:6px;font-family:var(--mono);font-size:.68rem;color:var(--txt2)">
              <svg width="28" height="4"><line x1="0" y1="2" x2="28" y2="2" stroke="#dc2626" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="5,4"/></svg> System Curve
            </div>
            <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:6px;font-family:var(--mono);font-size:.68rem;color:var(--txt2)">
              <svg width="28" height="4"><line x1="0" y1="2" x2="28" y2="2" stroke="#0ea5e9" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="3,3"/></svg> NPSHr
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Explanation table -->
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Curve / Point</th>
                <th>What It Shows</th>
                <th>How to Use It</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><strong style="color:var(--navy)">H-Q curve</strong></td>
                <td>Head (m) the pump delivers at each flow rate. Always falls from left (high head, zero flow) to right (low head, max flow).</td>
                <td>For your required flow Q, read up to this curve to find the head the pump will produce. Convert to pressure using P = &rho;gH.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Shutoff head</strong></td>
                <td>Maximum head at zero flow — where the H-Q curve meets the Y-axis. Pump is running but no fluid is moving.</td>
                <td>Never operate at shutoff for more than a few seconds. Heat builds rapidly in the casing and can damage the pump.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong style="color:var(--green)">BEP</strong></td>
                <td>Best Efficiency Point — the flow rate where the pump converts the most shaft power into useful hydraulic energy. Efficiency peaks here.</td>
                <td>Select a pump so normal operating flow is within &plusmn;10% of BEP. Operating far from BEP increases vibration, heat, and wear.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong style="color:var(--green)">&eta; curve</strong></td>
                <td>Pump efficiency (%) at each flow rate. Bell-shaped, peaking at BEP. Typical centrifugal pumps peak at 70&ndash;90%.</td>
                <td>Use to calculate shaft power: P_shaft = (&rho; &times; g &times; Q &times; H) / &eta;. Higher efficiency = lower running cost.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong style="color:var(--amber)">P curve</strong></td>
                <td>Shaft power (kW) drawn from the motor at each flow rate. For most centrifugal pumps, power rises with flow.</td>
                <td>Motor must be sized for the maximum power point on the curve (usually at max flow). Add 10&ndash;15% safety margin.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong style="color:var(--red)">System curve</strong></td>
                <td>The head your <em>system</em> demands at each flow rate: H_sys = static head + (friction losses &times; Q&sup2;). Parabola from the static head point.</td>
                <td>Draw your system curve on the pump curve. Where they intersect is the <strong>operating point</strong> — actual flow and head in service.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Operating point</strong></td>
                <td>The intersection of the H-Q curve and the system curve. This is where the pump will actually run.</td>
                <td>Read off the flow (Q) and head (H) — use this calculator to convert that head to pressure for your fluid.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong style="color:#0ea5e9">NPSHr curve</strong></td>
                <td>Net Positive Suction Head <em>required</em> by the pump at each flow. Rises steeply at high flows. Pump will cavitate if NPSHa &lt; NPSHr.</td>
                <td>Your available NPSHa (calculated from suction conditions) must always exceed NPSHr + 0.5 m safety margin. Use our NPSH Calculator.</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
