    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
        How do I convert metres of water to bar?
        <span class="arr">&#x25BE;</span>
      </button>
      <div class="faq-a">
        <div class="faq-ai">
          Multiply head in metres by fluid density and gravity, then divide by 100,000:
          <code>P (bar) = H (m) &times; &rho; (kg/m&sup3;) &times; 9.81 / 100,000</code>.
          For water at 20&deg;C (&rho; = 998.2 kg/m&sup3;): <code>P = H &times; 0.09791</code>.
          So 10 metres of water = 0.979 bar.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
        What is the difference between head and pressure?
        <span class="arr">&#x25BE;</span>
      </button>
      <div class="faq-a">
        <div class="faq-ai">
          <strong>Pressure</strong> (Pa, bar, psi) is force per unit area.
          <strong>Head</strong> is the equivalent height of fluid that generates that pressure: <code>H = P / (&rho; &times; g)</code>.
          1 bar = 10.2 m of water = 0.75 m of mercury.
          Pump engineers use head because pump curves in metres are valid for any fluid.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
        How do I convert psi to feet of water?
        <span class="arr">&#x25BE;</span>
      </button>
      <div class="faq-a">
        <div class="faq-ai">
          For water at 20&deg;C (SG = 0.998): <code>H (ft) = P (psi) &times; 2.308</code>.
          So 1 psi = 2.31 ft of water.
          Exact formula: <code>H (ft) = P (psi) &times; 6894.757 / (&rho; &times; 9.81 &times; 0.3048)</code>.
          For non-water fluids, divide the water result by the SG of your fluid.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
        Why does the same pump head produce different pressures for different fluids?
        <span class="arr">&#x25BE;</span>
      </button>
      <div class="faq-a">
        <div class="faq-ai">
          Because <code>&Delta;P = &rho; &times; g &times; H</code> &mdash; pressure depends on fluid density.
          A pump producing 50 m of head gives 4.89 bar with water but 9.01 bar with sulfuric acid (1840 kg/m&sup3;).
          Pump curves use head precisely because head is independent of fluid density.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
        How does temperature affect head-to-pressure conversion?
        <span class="arr">&#x25BE;</span>
      </button>
      <div class="faq-a">
        <div class="faq-ai">
          Higher temperature &rarr; lower density (most liquids) &rarr; less pressure per metre of head.
          For water, this is about 0.2% per 10&deg;C.
          For organic solvents the thermal expansion is 4&ndash;7&times; higher &mdash;
          temperature correction is much more important.
          This calculator applies temperature-corrected density automatically using each fluid's expansion coefficient.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

